		<div class="content">
			<div id="post_message_221951">
				<blockquote class="postcontent restore">
					<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Chewi</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=6de918634ecde75fa99c9a66a4b8055c&amp;p=221948#post221948" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I've said it time and again, let the distributions handle it. They know their own systems best.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>That sounds like a silly way to handle the problem. Now a commercial software vendor is tied to a package maintainer for each and every distribution they want to support. Not only that, but the vendor is also now living by the package maintainer's schedule. The vendor can no longer provide release dates; the package maintainer sets the release date. The vendor can no longer push out timely updates; the package maintainer has to approve each update. And let's not forget that many distributions might simply refuse to package the vendor's software for any number of reasons.<br />
<br />
There are way too many downsides to this idea.
				</blockquote>
			</div>

			


		</div>
			
				
			
			
			
		</div>
